  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD059315",
      "title": "Molecular basis of vitamin K driven \u03b3-carboxylation at membrane interface",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "The \u03b3-carboxylation of glutamate residues enables Ca2+-mediated membrane assembly of protein complexes that support broad physiological functions including hemostasis, calcium homeostasis, immune response, and endocrine regulation. Modulating \u03b3-carboxylation level provides prevalent treatments for hemorrhagic and thromboembolic diseases. This unique posttranslational modification requires vitamin K hydroquinone (KH2) to drive highly demanding reactions catalyzed by the membrane-integrated \u03b3-carboxylase (VKGC). To decipher underlying mechanisms, we determined cryo-electron microscopy structures of human VKGC in unbound form, with KH2 and four hemostatic and non-hemostatic proteins possessing propeptides and glutamate-rich domains in different carboxylation states. VKGC recognizes substrate proteins via knob-and-hole interactions with propeptides, thereby bringing tethered glutamate-containing segments for processive carboxylation within a large chamber that provides steric control. Propeptide binding also triggers a global conformational change to signal VKGC activation. Through sequential deprotonation and KH2 epoxidation, VKGC generates free hydroxide ion as an exceptionally strong base required to deprotonate the \u03b3-carbon of glutamate for CO2 addition. The diffusion of this superbase, protected and guided by a sealed hydrophobic tunnel, elegantly resolves the challenge of coupling KH2 epoxidation to \u03b3-carboxylation across the membrane interface. These structural insights and extensive functional experiments advance membrane enzymology and propel the development of novel treatments for \u03b3-carboxylation disorders.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "For the detection of \u03b3-carboxylated osteocalcin produced in cells, HEK 293S GnTI- cells expressing the osteocalcin-BRIL-VKGC fusion protein were cultured for 3 days in Freestyle medium with 20 \u03bcM vitamin K to promote \u03b3-carboxylation. Subsequently, the fusion protein was purified and processed using a filter aided sample preparation (FASP) method. 200 \u00b5L of 8 M urea were added to 20 \u03bcg of the purified protein and then loaded onto a Microcon centrifugal filter (Millipore Sigma, 30 kDa cutoff) pre-washed with 100 mM [NH4]HCO3. The mixture was centrifuged at 10,000 \u00d7 g for 30 min at 4\u00b0C, followed by three washes with urea through repeated centrifugation. The denatured protein was reduced by incubation with 100 \u00b5L of 50 mM tris-(2-carboxyethyl)phosphine (TCEP) at 37\u00b0C for 30 min, and then alkylated with 100 \u00b5L of 100 mM iodoacetamide (IAA) at room temperature in the dark for 30 min.  The mixtures were centrifuged at 12,000 \u00d7 g for 30 min at 4\u00b0C, followed by three washes with 100 \u00b5L of 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 through repeated centrifugation. Subseqently, the samples were digested with 1 \u00b5g trypsin in 50 \u00b5L of 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 and 0.05% ProteaseMax for 14 h in a 37\u00b0C water bath. Tryptic peptides were collected through centrifugation at 12,000 \u00d7 g for 30 min, with another wash of 50 \u00b5L 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 to retrieve the remnants. The peptide concentration was measured using a Nanodrop Microvolume Spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific) and further diluted to a concentration of ~0.1 mg/mL with 1% formic acid (FA) and 2% acetonitrile (ACN) in H2O for subsequent MS analyses.   The samples were analyzed by online nanoflow liquid chromatography tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) using electron-transfer dissociation (ETD) using an Orbitrap Ascend Tribrid Mass Spectrometer (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA) with a Nanospray Flex source (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA) coupled online to an Vanquish Neo UHPLC System (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA). Samples of 2 \u00b5L, containing ~200 ng peptides, were loaded onto an Easy-Spray\u2122 PepMap\u2122 Neo 2 \u03bcm C18, 75 \u03bcm \u00d7 150 mm microcapillary column. Analysis was performed at room temperature using a 110-minute MS method at a flow rate of 0.300 \u00b5L/min with the following gradient profile: (min:%B) 0:0; 95:30; 105:45; 105.5:95; 110:95. The Orbitrap Ascend Tribrid Mass Spectrometer was operated in data-dependent positive ion mode acquiring ETD MS/MS scans after each MS1 scan (resolution = 120,000, standard AGC target) on the most abundant ions using an intensity threshold of 1 \u00d7 104. The maximum injection time utilized for MS/MS scans was 100 ms using the ion trap, with ion trap scan rate set to rapid and a first mass of 110 m/z. The dynamic exclusion time was set to 6 s, with the isotope exclusion function enabled. Charge inclusion was enabled for charge states 2-5 with mass range of 300-950 m/z, and charge states 6-8.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Samples were analyzed using PMI Byos PTM workflow (v5.7.45 x64). The following parameters were used to analyze osteocalcin-BRIL-VKGC fusion protein samples: 20ppm precursor tolerance, ETD fragmentation, 0.4Da fragment tolerance, C-terminal fully specific cleavage at arginine and lysine residues, 2 missed cleavage, 10,000 max precursor charge, 1% FDR, and the following modifications (allowing for 4 common and 1 rare): Oxidation (rare1, +15.994915 @ M, W), Carboxylation (common3, +43.989829 @ E), and carbamidomethylation (fixed, +57.021464 @ C). The following sequence for osteocalcin-BRIL-VKGC fusion protein was used for analysis: ",
